CHOLERA - ARMENIA
*****************
A ProMED-mail post
<http://www.healthnet.org/programs/promed.html>
[1]
Date: Mon, 7 Sep 1998 19:05:34 -0400
Source: World Reporter, 6 Sep 1998
Via: GPHIN

About 50 residents of a village near the Armenian capital Yerevan have
fallen ill with a mild form of cholera [according to] the Armenian Health
Ministry.
A statement issued by the ministry on 5th September said that the strain
was "not very contagious" and that the course of the disease was generally
favorable. Patients and those in contact with them had been placed under
observation. The centre of the infection - the village water supply - had
been localized. The outbreak took place
in the of the village of Zartonk in Oktemberyan District in Armavir Region.
Zartonk itself is 35 km west of Yerevan. Those infected suffered acute
intestinal complaints and have all been hospitalized, the agency said.
************
[2]
Date: Mon, 07 Sep 1998 10:26:14 -0500
Source: News media, 7 Sep 1998
Via: Clyde Markon <docmarkon@worldnet.att.net>

The [outbreak] of cholera in the village of Zatonk, 35 kilometers west of
Yerevan, has been localized, sources in the Armenian government [report].
All those infected have been hospitalized, [and] all the other residents of
the village, mainly Yezid Kurds, are being thoroughly examined by medics.
